      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Chronic cholecystitis with cholelithiasis (with adhered liver tissue)
Microscopic descriotion:</div><div>The gallbladder shows intact, chronically inflamed mucosa accompanied by formation of Rokitansky sinuses within the underlying muscular coat. Adhered liver tissue is also seen. No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Chronic follicular cholecystitis.</title>
    <created>20250612T020035Z</created>
    <updated>20250612T020050Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Chronic follicular cholecystitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The gallbladder shows intact, chronically inflamed mucosa accompanied by formation of Rokitansky sinuses within the underlying muscular coat. Prominent lymphoid follicles with germinal centers formation are seen. Pyloric metaplasia is also noted. No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>combined hepatocellular-cholangiocarcinoma</title>
    <created>20220425T031506Z</created>
    <updated>20220425T031632Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>combined hepatocellular-cholangiocarcinoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show histologic evidence of both hepatocellular and biliary differentiation by morphology, and supported by</div><div>immunohistochemistry.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Consistent with autoimmune hepatitis</title>
    <created>20160628T092557Z</created>
    <updated>20170602T083106Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>DIAGNOSIS:<br clear="none" />Consistent with autoimmune hepatitis, liver, right lobe, echo-guided random biopsy<br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />CLINICAL INFORMATION: <br clear="none" />-- 2016-6-25: GOT(88 U/L), bilirubin direct(10.34 mg/dL), alkaline phosphatase(351    <br clear="none" />              IU/L), r-GT (116.3 IU/L). <br clear="none" />-- AFP 2.4 ng/mL<br clear="none" />-- Antinuclear Ab 160x(+), anto-ds DNA &lt;0.5 IU/mL, anti-smooth muscle Ab 20x(-)<br clear="none" />-- Anti-HCV (-), HBsAg &lt;0.05.<br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />GROSS DESCRIPTION:<br clear="none" />The specimen is composed of two pieces of brown tissue, measuring up to 2 x 0.1 x 0.1 <br clear="none" />cm.<br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />All are embedded in one cassette.<br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:<br clear="none" />It shows liver tissue cores revealing periportal interface activity and fibrosis as <br clear="none" />well as lobular inflammation accompanied by ductular proliferation and cholestasis. <br clear="none" />The inflammatory infiltrate includes lymphocytes, neutrophils, eosinophils, and <br clear="none" />histiocytes. Hepatocyte swelling and acidophilic bodies are also seen. <br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />Immunohistochemically, no viral inclusion is demonstrated by anti-CMV immunostain. CK7<br clear="none" />highlights the ductular proliferation. CD31 demonstrates the sinusoidal <br clear="none" />capillarization <br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />No fungus is seen by GMS and PAS. <br clear="none" /><br clear="none" />The overall features are consistent with an autoimmune hepatitis. However, drug-<br clear="none" />induced hepatitis cannot be completely excluded. Please correlate with clinical <br clear="none" />information. <br clear="none" /><br clear="none" /><br clear="none" /><br clear="none" /><br clear="none" /><br clear="none" /></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Consistent with polycystic disease, liver</title>
    <created>20161203T023510Z</created>
    <updated>20161203T023532Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show cystic lesions lined by flattened or cuboidal biliary epithelium. Mononuclear inflammatory infiltrate is focally seen. The hepatic trabecular cords show atrophy adjacent to the cysts. Calcification is noted along the cystic wall. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>focal nodular hyperplasia. FNH</title>
    <created>20210914T024539Z</created>
    <updated>20251229T053918Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Focal nodular hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show nodules composed of benign-looking hepatocytes arranged in plates no more than 2 cells in thickness. The central scar contains large dystrophic vessels, numerous small arterioles with a lymphocytic infiltrate. At the interface of fibrous regions, a ductular reaction is highlighted by CK19 immunostaining. Focal area shows sinusoidal dilatation with congestion. The sinusoidal endothelium shows patchy CD34 staining. GS is focally positive. Reticulin stain shows no loss of reticulin framework in tumor part.</div><div>Taken together, this is a focal nodular hyperplasia.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>GAL focal abscess.</title>
    <created>20181003T053952Z</created>
    <updated>20250904T084709Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Acute cholecystitis with focal abscess and cholelithiasis.</div><div>Acute cholecystitis with focal abscess.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections reveal partial mucosal destruction and inflamed wall that is infiltrated by numerous polymorphonuclear as well as mononuclear cells in its lamina propria as well as the underlying muscular coat. The wall shows edema, hyperemia, extravasation of RBCs and myofibroblastic proliferation. Focal abscess formation is seen.
No malignancy is observed.</div><div>    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
