  <note>
    <title>GAL5+ cholesterosis</title>
    <created>20170224T081812Z</created>
    <updated>20260522T045748Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Chronic cholecystitis with cholelithiasis and cholesterosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Representative sections are taken and submitted in one cassette.</div><div><br/></div><div>Chronic cholecystitis with cholelithiasis and cholesterosis.</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The gallbladder shows intact, chronically inflamed mucosa accompanied by formation of Rokitansky sinuses within the underlying muscular coat. Cholesterosis is seen. No evidence of malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>Gross: There are focal /diffuse yellow, flat deposits on mucosal surface.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>GAL6 Cholelithiasis with acute and chronic cholecystitis.</title>
    <created>20170206T053045Z</created>
    <updated>20260522T051216Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Cholelithiasis with acute and chronic cholecystitis.</span></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections reveal partial mucosal destruction and inflamed wall that is infiltrated by numerous polymorphonuclear as well as mononuclear cells in its lamina propria as well as the underlying muscular coat. The wall shows edema, hyperemia and extravasation of RBCs. <span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses are seen. </span>No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Cholelithiasis with acute and chronic cholecystitis</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div>Sections reveal partial mucosal destruction and inflamed wall that is infiltrated by mononuclear cells with hemosiderin-laden macrophages accompanied by fibrosis. Bile pigment depositions associated with foreign body reaction are also seen. One piece of liver tissue is seen with fatty change. No malignancy is observed.</div><hr/><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 11pt;">acute and chronic cholecystitis.</span></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections reveal partial mucosal destruction and inflamed</div><div>wall that is infiltrated by numerous polymorphonuclear as    </div><div>well as mononuclear cells in its lamina propia as well as</div><div>the underlying muscular coat. The wall shows edema,</div><div>hyperemia and extravasation of RBCs. No malignancy is observed.    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>GB- pyloric</title>
    <created>20240918T054214Z</created>
    <updated>20240918T054401Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>pyloric gland metaplasia</div><div><br/></div><div>polypoid pyloric gland collection in the mucosa</div><div><br/></div><ul><li><div>ref: Clinical Keys - Book - Pathology - Oddy..... GI</div></li></ul></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Glutamine synthetase GS</title>
