    <updated>20200226T015256Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Glutamine synthetase is present in the pericentral hepatocytes.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>HCC</title>
    <created>20170303T003350Z</created>
    <updated>20250220T050043Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">Hepatocellular carcinoma.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Section shows tissue cores containing sheets of neoplastic hepatocellular cells arranged in thick trabecular pattern with focally clear cell change. No bile ducts are seen within the tumor area.</span></div><div><br/></div><ul><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Masson's trichrome demonstrats the fibrotic bands in non-tumorous part.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Reticulin stain shows loss of reticulin framework in tumor part.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">The reticulin stain shows disruption of normal reticulin framework and thickening of the cell plates in tumorous part.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">CD34 stain demonstrates diffusely increased sinusoidal capillarization in tumor, supporting the diagnosis of HCC.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">CD34 stain demonstrates sinusoidal capillarization.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Tumor and non-tumor areas both show focal cytoplasmic staining for HbcAg.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">The tumor cells are negative for GPC-3 and CK19. Compared with the findings between the tumor and non-tumorous part, the staining results of HSP-70 and GS are not contributory.</span></div></li><li><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">CK7demonstrates the normal distribution of bile ducts within portal area.</span></div></li></ul><div><br/></div><div>    </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Liver</title>
    <created>20140815T095118Z</created>
    <updated>20170303T003358Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div>Clinical information, Lab data</div><div>-- Viral test: HBsAg (_IU/mL), Anti-HCV ()<br clear="none" />
-- Tumor markers: AFP (_) <br clear="none" />
-- CT (201_-_): </div><br clear="none" /></div><div><br/></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><p><br clear="none" /></p></div><div><p><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">HCC, non-tumor太小無法評估 2014071008</span><br clear="none" /></p><p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">The inflammation activity of the non-tumorous liver parenchyma is difficult to be evaluated and will be overestimated, due to the fact that the tumor almost occupied the entire specimen with very little non-tumorous part left for evaluation. The non-tumorous part immediately adjacent to the tumor shows extensive hemorrhage and reactive changes.</span></p><p><br clear="none" /></p><p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">A subcapsular wedge biopsy is note recommended to evaluate a diffuse disease such as chronic hepatitis because fibrous septa extending from the capsule into the underlying parenchyma may prompt an overestimation of fibrosis and nonspecific inflammation related to the surgical procedure may influence assessment of the grade of inflammation. </span></p><div>Regenerative nodule</div><div style="padding-left: 30px;">Sections show regenerative nodules with reduced and scattered portal tracts. There is focal increased cellularity, but without overt cytologic atypia. Immunohistochemically, the hepatic cells are negative for GPC-3. Staining for CD34 shows no significant increase of sinusoidal capillarization. Staining for HSP-70 shows no difference between the nodules and surrounding hepatic tissue. The reticulin stain shows focally mild disruption of normal reticulin framework with cell plates of 1-3 cells thick in the nodules.</div><div><br clear="none" /></div><br clear="none" /></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><br clear="none" /></div><div style="padding-left: 30px;"><br clear="none" /></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Liver cirrhosis with a focus of atypical adenomatous hyperplasia (dysplastic nodule) [biopsy]</title>
    <created>20190404T064507Z</created>
    <updated>20190404T064622Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Liver cirrhosis with a focus of atypical adenomatous hyperplasia (dysplastic nodule) (Please see description).</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>Section shows liver cirrhosis. A tiny focus shows mildly increased in hepatocytic nuclear size, cellularity and presence of unpaired artery. </div><div>HSP70 and GS stains are not increased in this focus. GPC3 stain is negative. Atypical adenomatous hyperplasia/dysplastic nodule</div><div>is favored. The morphology and immunostaining markers do not reach the diagnostic criteria of heptocellular carcinoma by</div><div>these specimens. However, sampling problem is possible. Clinical correlation is recommended.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Necrotizing cholecystitis</title>
    <created>20170425T042210Z</created>
    <updated>20260522T051639Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Necrotizing cholecystitis</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The gallbladder shows hemorrhagic as well as liquefactive</div><div>necrosis of the entire wall with intense PMN infiltration</div><div>and fibrin exudation. </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Small cell carcinoma, metastatic</title>
    <created>20250424T073031Z</created>
    <updated>20250424T082244Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Small cell carcinoma, metastatic.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows hepatic tissue infiltrated by sheets and nests</div><div>of neoplastic cells revealing medium sized cells with</div><div>necrosis and crush artifact. The tumor cells show finely</div><div>granular chromatin and scant cytoplasm. Nuclear molding is</div><div>also seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for</div><div>synaptophysin and INSM1 but not TTF-1 or p40. Together with</div><div>clinico-radiological findings, metastastic small cell</div><div>carcinoma is diagnosed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Small cell carcinoma.</title>
    <created>20250424T073127Z</created>
    <updated>20250424T082240Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Small cell carcinoma. See Comment.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section reveals liver tissue infiltrated by sheets and nests</div><div>of neoplastic cells. The tumor is composed of medium-sized</div><div>cells exhibiting tumor necrosis. The neoplastic cells</div><div>display finely granular chromatin, inconspicuous nucleoli,</div><div>scant cytoplasm, and nuclear molding.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for</div><div>AE1/AE3, synaptophysin, and show focal positivity for</div><div>chromogranin A. The cells are negative for arginase-1.</div><div>Ki-67 shows a high proliferative index.</div><div><br/></div><div>Comment: These findings are consistent with small cell</div><div>carcinoma. Given the location, metastatic disease should be</div><div>strongly considered.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Solitary biliary cyst, liver</title>
    <created>20170227T030121Z</created>
    <updated>20170227T030142Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show cystic tissue lined by bland-looking cuboidal epithelium. Liver tissue is seen in its wall. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Xanthogranulomatous cholecystitis with cholelithiasis, gallbladder, laparoscopic  cholecystectomy</title>
    <created>20170117T061924Z</created>
    <updated>20251021T074854Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>The gallbladder shows ulcerative mucosa accompanied by heavy collections of mixed  inflammatory cells and abundant foamy histiocytes with fibroblasts/myofibroblasts  proliferation. Formation of Rokitansky sinuses within the underlying muscular coat is  </div><div>also seen. No evidence of  malignancy is noted.  </div><div>aa</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
</en-export>
